          "text": "<p><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The Elastic Recoil of the Lungs will be Maximal</span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">A 58-year-old male with a history of chronic bronchitis presents to his primary care physician for a routine check-up. He has been stable on his current medication regimen and reports no new respiratory symptoms. At the end of normal respiration (exhalation), which of the following statements best describes the relationship between the Elastic Recoil of the Lungs and the Chest Wall?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q4111912",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 33420,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        2
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. C) The Elastic Recoil of the Lungs and the Chest Wall exactly Balance Each Other</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option C:&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">At the end of a normal exhalation, the <strong>inward elastic recoil</strong> of the lungs is <strong>exactly balanced</strong> by the <strong>outward recoil</strong> of the chest wall, maintaining <strong>functional residual capacity</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><strong>Option A:</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Incorrect</strong>. At the end of a normal exhalation, the elastic recoil of the lungs is not greater than that of the chest wall. Instead, they are in <strong>balance</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><strong>Option B:</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Incorrect</strong>. The elastic recoil of the lungs is not lower than that of the chest wall at the end of a normal exhalation; they are <strong>balanced</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><strong>Option D:</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Incorrect</strong>. The elastic recoil of the lungs is not maximal at the end of a normal exhalation. It is <strong>balanced</strong> with the <strong>chest wall&#39;s recoil</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">To understand the <strong>mechanics</strong> of <strong>breathing</strong>, particularly the <strong>balance between</strong> the <strong>elastic recoil</strong> of the <strong>lungs</strong> and the <strong>chest wall</strong> at the <strong>end</strong> of a <strong>normal exhalation</strong>, which is crucial in <strong>maintaining lung volumes</strong> and <strong>respiratory function</strong>, especially in patients with <strong>chronic respiratory conditions</strong> like <strong>bronchitis</strong>.Top of Form</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology, 2<sup>nd</sup> South Asia Edition, Pg no: 342</span></strong></span></span></p>",
