      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">In a Critical Care Unit, a patient with Severe Anemia and Hypoxia is being treated. The Medical Team discusses the primary Mode of Oxygen Transport in the Blood, Crucial for managing the patient&#39;s condition. Which of the following will be the Predominant Mode of Transport of Oxygen in the Blood?</span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q9570094",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 33421,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        2
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. C) Oxyhemoglobin</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option C:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> Correct. The <strong>majority</strong> of <strong>oxygen</strong> in the blood is carried bound to <strong>hemoglobin</strong> as <strong>oxyhemoglobin</strong>, which is <strong>efficient</strong> in <strong>transporting oxygen</strong> from the <strong>lungs</strong> to the <strong>tissues</strong>. (<strong>98- 99%).</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/02/26/21.jpg\" style=\"height:276px; width:500px\" /></strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option A</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">.&nbsp;<strong>Incorrect</strong>. <strong>Oxygen</strong> is <strong>poorly soluble</strong> in <strong>blood</strong>; only a <strong>very small amount</strong> is carried in <strong>free form</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option B</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">.&nbsp;<strong>Incorrect</strong>. While oxygen is dissolved in the <strong>plasma</strong>, this accounts for only a <strong>small fraction</strong> of the <strong>total oxygen transport</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option D</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">.&nbsp;<strong>Incorrect</strong>. Carbonic acid is involved in the <strong>transport</strong> of <strong>carbon dioxide</strong>, not oxygen.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Identify <strong>oxyhemoglobin</strong> as the <strong>predominant mode</strong> of <strong>oxygen</strong> <strong>transport</strong> in the <strong>blood</strong>.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ref: Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology, 2<sup>nd</sup> South Asia Edition, Pg no: 371</span></strong></span></span></p>",
